%N A386642 Roll n fair, distinguishable, n-sided dice and sort the dice in increasing order with the lowest on the left, highest on the right. Let m be the maximum value rolled and select the m-th die from the right. Then a(n) is the number of such rolls (over all n^n possible outcomes) where the selected die shows 1.
%C A386642 Let p be the probability that the selected die shows 1; i.e., p = a(n)/n^n. Jameson conjectured (2025) that the limiting value of p is between 0.46 and 0.47. Tim Large conjectured (2025) that the limiting value of p is 1 - exp((1/e) - 1) = 0.4685....
%F A386642 Conjecture: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} ( (n-k+1)^n - Sum_{j=0..k-1} binomial(n, j)*(n-k)^(n-j) - (n-k)^n + Sum_{j=0..k-1} binomial(n, j)*(n-k-1)^(n-j) ) + 1.
%F A386642 a(n) = 1 + Sum_{k=1..n-1} ( binomial(n,k) * ((n-1)^k-(k-1)^k) ). - _Christian Sievers_, Aug 08 2025
%e A386642 When n=1, there is one single-sided die, which always shows 1. So a(1)=1.
%e A386642 When n=2, there are two two-sided dice. There are three rolls for which the selected die shows 1: {1,1}, {1,2}, and {2,1}. For example, a roll of {2,1} is sorted as (1,2); since the maximum value rolled is 2 (i.e., m=2), the second die from the right is selected; this die shows 1. So a(2)=3.
%e A386642 When n=3, there are three three-sided dice. There are 16 rolls for which the selected die shows 1: {1,1,1}, {1,1,2}, {1,1,3}, {1,2,1}, {1,2,3}, {1,3,1}, {1,3,2}, {1,3,3}, {2,1,1}, {2,1,3}, {2,3,1}, {3,1,1}, {3,1,2}, {3,1,3}, {3,2,1}, and {3,3,1}. For example, a roll of {1,2,1} is sorted as (1,1,2); since the maximum value rolled is 2 (i.e., m=2), the second die from the right is selected; this die shows 1. So a(3)=16.
%o A386642 (PARI) a(n)=1+sum(k=1,n-1,binomial(n,k)*((n-1)^k-(k-1)^k)) \\ _Christian Sievers_, Aug 08 2025
